(firstQuint)Comparison of Effects of Intravenous Midazolam and Ketamine on Emergence Agitation.

 Emergence agitation is self-limiting aggressive behavior that develops in the early period of awakening from anesthesia.

 A high level of preoperative anxiety is a risk factor for emergence agitation using Aono's four-point scale.

 Midazolam and ketamine was administered to the patients to decrease of preoperative anxiety.

 We aimed to compare the emergence agitation between midazolam group and ketamine group.

